definition.value: An isothiocyanate having a butyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A quaternary ammonium ion resulting from the methylation of the nitrogen atom of alpha-berbine.
A monoterpenoid that is 4,5,6,7-tetrahydro-1-benzofuran substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 6.
A salt of the organic compound tartaric acid.

One of a class of monoterpenoids biosynthesized from isoprene and often intermediates in the biosynthesis of alkaloids. Iridoids usually consist of a cyclopentane ring fused to a six-membered oxygen heterocycle; cleavage of a bond in the cyclopentane ring gives rise to the subclass known as secoiridoids.
An agent, with unique chemical structure and biochemical requirements, which generates nitric oxide.
An EC 3.1.4.* (phosphoric diester hydrolase) inhibitor which interferes with the  action of 3',5'-cyclic-nucleotide phosphodiesterase (EC 3.1.4.17).
An octadecenoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of trans-2-octadecenoic acid.
A 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 3-oxooctadecanoic acid.
An octadec-2-enoic acid having a trans- double bond.
An octadecenoic acid with the double bond at position 2.
An octadec-2-enoic acid having a cis- double bond.
A 3-oxo fatty acid derived from stearic acid.
A 3-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid in which the chiral centre has S configuration.
Any aliphatic alcohol in which the carbon chain contains one or more olefinic bonds.
